			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Our Job...who knows it us or the casters?<a name="6562"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 22 03 2:56 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I definately understand the frustration with someone telling you how to play your class.  If they are demanding that you sing mana song nonstop, BAH! But that is not always whats going on.
<br />

<br />
Let's assume, for the sake of this discussion, that you are a really good bard, you know your songs like the back of your hand, and you are creative in deciding what twist is best in the moment.
<br />

<br />
Let's also assume you do NOT have that same level of familiarity with enchanter, or shaman, or druid, or cleric, or fill-in-the-blank spells.  
<br />

<br />
Lets assume the caster in question has a bard alt and is similarly familiar with Bard songs.
<br />

<br />
It is a possiblity that the caster is trying to maximize your COMBINED efforts.  It is also a possibility that the caster is a meddlesome fool.  But in the former case, you might be stepping on each others toes without YOU realizing it and so the caster is requesting a change of twist. (ex. Enchanter hasting and you singing basic haste song, you are better off singing over-haste and something else.  If you don't realize this and the enchanter does then the answer is HE knows how to play a bard better than YOU, unless there are other factors in play)
<br />

<br />
I generally try not to be nasty about it.  If a single individual is making what seem like inappropriate suggestions to me, I take it to (civil) tells with them.  I ask what ISSUE they are trying to address with their song requests.  I decide if they have a point, in my opinion, and consider a possible song change, or other strategy to address the issue.  Strategies may include a suggestion aof a change in what THEY are doing, or what the group as a whole is doing..
<br />

<br />
(ex. You tell Wizbang Pissmanaaway: 'OOM alot,hmmm?..Cleric is at 70m, Shaman is at 75m, Tank is at full health, maybe you should ease up on the nukes a little.  I'll sing mana for you as much as I reasonably can, but I can't during the fight, sorry. Do me a favor and sit by the cleric so you can both be in range, OK?  Try to balance your mana with the cleric for our maximum efficency, if they are ahead of you, sit one out, let the tank suck it up')
<br />

<br />
The above example is a wizard that not only doesn't know how to play our class, but is making mistakes as a wizard.  
<br />
Did I just tell him how to play HIS class?  Yeah.  
<br />
Did he NEED someone to tell him? Yeah.
<br />
Was I out of line in the suggestions? Nah.
<br />
Can that happen in the reverse, with a caster making suggestions to a bard who is not considering all the factors while the caster is thinking more clearly than the bard?  Yeah.
<br />

<br />
So relax, take it easy, and consider whether there might be a point before you dismiss a request.  When the request is a bad idea, be firm but civil, and find out why they were thinking it would be good, deal with the why.
<br />

<br />
Reys
<br />
</span></td>
